Package com.github.tommyettinger.crux

Interface Point5<P extends Point5<P>>

Type Parameters:
P - in implementing types, this is the implementing type
All Superinterfaces:
PointN<P>
public interface Point5<P extends Point5<P>> extends PointN<P>
A minimal super-interface that can be implemented by 5D PointN types. There are no current 5D point classes that could implement this in libGDX or other evaluated libraries, so any implementing class would need to start from "scratch" and the support provided by PointN. Five-dimensional points can be used to represent a handful of uncommon things, but they seem most useful for simply representing points in 5D space. An example usage would be to make a looping animation of a 3D object by moving 5D points through 3D space and 2D time, with both the space and time taking equal-length circular paths. That probably doesn't make much sense to most people, and likewise, most people won't ever need to think about 5D space -- or to use this interface.

    • xi

      default int xi()
      Gets the first (x) coordinate. Always gets an int; if PointN.floatingPoint() is true, this defaults to casting x() to an int. Implementations where floatingPoint() is false should override this and return their actual int data.
      Returns:
      the first (x) coordinate, as an int

    • x

      P x(float next)
      Sets the first (x) coordinate to next. Always takes a float, even if PointN.floatingPoint() is false. For mutable types, this should edit this value in-place. For immutable types, it must return a new value.
      Parameters:
      next - the new value for the first (x) coordinate
      Returns:
      if this is mutable, then this value after editing; if this is immutable, then a different edited point
